      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the pancetta and soffritto",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large, heavy pot over medium-low heat. Add {{pancetta}} of pancetta and cook for 5 minutes until the fat renders. Add {{onion}} diced onion, {{celery}} diced celery and {{carrot}} diced carrot. Cook gently for 12 to 15 minutes, stirring occasionally, until completely soft. Add {{garlic}} of chopped garlic; cook for 2 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the meat",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Raise the heat to medium-high. Add {{beef-mince}} of beef mince and {{pork-mince}} of pork mince. Break up with a wooden spoon and cook for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the meat is deeply browned and any liquid has evaporated. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add wine, milk and tomato",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pour in {{white-wine-dry}} of white wine. Let it bubble and reduce until almost completely gone, about 5 minutes. Pour in {{whole-milk}} of milk; reduce again until absorbed, about 5 minutes. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, {{tomato-puree}} of tomato purée, {{nutmeg-ground}} of nutmeg and {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves. Stir well.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Simmer low and slow",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Reduce to the lowest possible heat. Place the lid on the pot slightly ajar. Cook for 1.5 to 2 hours, stirring every 20 minutes, adding a splash of water if the sauce looks dry. The finished ragù should be dense, meaty and pale-orange rather than red. Remove the bay leaves and adjust seasoning before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Bolognese has very little tomato; only half a tin is traditional. If using too much, add more milk and cook longer. A 2-hour minimum at very low heat is the fix.",
              "cause": "Too much tomato, or not enough cooking time.",
              "symptom": "Sauce is very red and tastes of tomato"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use mince with some fat content. The milk step is there to prevent this; add it and cook until absorbed.",
              "cause": "Lean mince, or too high heat during browning.",
              "symptom": "Meat is grainy and dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use the lowest hob setting, with the lid slightly ajar. A heat diffuser helps on gas.",
              "cause": "Heat too high during the long simmer.",
              "symptom": "Sauce catching on the bottom"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bologna is the gastronomic capital of Italy, and the ragù is its signature contribution. The registered recipe from 1982 codified what Bolognese home cooks had been making for generations. It belongs on a Sunday: a pot started in the morning, the house filling with the low, sweet smell of meat and wine, ready for a late lunch with wide pasta and good Parmesan.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
